        <h1>{pageTitle}</h1>
        <p class="dek">
          What the IMF's own post-mortems and free-market economists actually blame, where they disagree with each other and which popular explanations don't survive contact with the data.
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="article">
        <section id="overview" aria-labelledby="overview-heading">
          <h2 id="overview-heading">Overview</h2>
          <p>
            Argentina's GDP per capita did grow after 1990. In constant 2021 PPP dollars it rose from about <a href="https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.PCAP.PP.KD?locations=AR" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">$17,000 in 1990 to $26,800 in 2024</a>, a 57% gain. That sounds respectable until you annualize it (1.34% a year) and compare it with plausible peers over the same window: Uruguay grew about 128%, Chile 176% and Poland 252%. Worse, all of Argentina's net progress happened before 2011. The <a href="https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.PCAP.KD?locations=AR" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">World Bank series in constant 2015 dollars</a> peaked at $14,041 in 2011 and stood at $12,774 in 2024, 9% below the peak. The IMF's <a href="https://www.imf.org/-/media/files/publications/cr/2026/english/1argea2026001.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">2026 Article IV consultation</a> puts the 2011-2024 decline at close to 15%, using a different national-accounts vintage. The estimates differ, but both show more than a decade without lasting per-capita growth in a country that ranked among the world's ten richest around 1913.
          </p>
          <p>
            The 2007-2015 data are less reliable because Argentina falsified its official statistics. After Néstor Kirchner replaced senior INDEC staff in early 2007, official inflation ran at a fraction of private estimates (<a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-02-01/argentina-becomes-first-nation-censured-by-imf-on-inflation-data" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">10.8% official versus 25.6% private for 2011</a>) and GDP was overstated accordingly. In February 2013 the IMF issued a <a href="https://www.imf.org/en/news/articles/2015/09/14/01/49/pr1333" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">declaration of censure</a> against Argentina, the first in the Fund's history. It <a href="https://www.imf.org/en/News/Articles/2016/11/09/PR16497-Argentina-IMF-Executive-Board-Removes-Declaration-of-Censure" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">lifted the censure in November 2016</a> after the statistics agency was rebuilt. Treat figures from that window cautiously.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="the-core-disease" aria-labelledby="the-core-disease-heading">
          <h2 id="the-core-disease-heading">The core disease</h2>
          <p>
            The same combination kept recurring. Governments adopted monetary or exchange-rate anchors inconsistent with fiscal policy, financed the gap by printing pesos or borrowing in dollars, resisted adjustment with controls and repeatedly changed the rules. Each crisis destroyed savings, credit, investment and productivity.
          </p>
          <p>
            The University of Chicago history, Nicolás Cachanosky, the World Bank and the IMF all put fiscal dominance near the root of the problem, though deficits alone do not explain every crisis. The <a href="https://manifold.bfi.uchicago.edu/read/case-of-argentina/section/9905ef24-8c94-42ad-adf7-068efb4d9afb" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Chicago monetary-and-fiscal history</a> dates a structural break in Argentina's deficit behavior to 1991 (when convertibility briefly ended inflation) and notes that after 2010 inflation rose again and per-capita income stopped growing. Cachanosky puts <a href="https://www.bloomberglinea.com/english/argentina-can-dollarize-in-2024-without-limiting-growth-says-nicolas-cachanosky/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">average annual inflation since 1940 at 60%</a>, punctuated by hyperinflations. The country has defaulted on its sovereign debt nine times, three of them since 2001. The <a href="https://documents1.worldbank.org/curated/en/099061224182598390/pdf/P1749671ac038b03e1bc271505e88eab550.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">World Bank's country economic memorandum</a> ranks macroeconomic volatility driven by procyclical fiscal policy as the first of three binding constraints on growth, ahead of restrictive trade policy and declining human capital. The <a href="https://www.imf.org/-/media/files/publications/cr/2022/english/1argea2022001.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">IMF's 2022 program</a> treated ending monetary financing of the deficit as the precondition for everything else.
          </p>
          <p>
            The damage compounds through finance. Because the peso cannot be trusted, Argentines hold well over $200 billion in physical dollars and offshore accounts; domestic credit to the private sector is <a href="https://www.cato.org/free-society/fall-2025/liberty-versus-power-mileis-argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">about 15% of GDP, versus 71% in Brazil, 109% in Chile and 192% in the United States</a>. Firms that cannot borrow cannot invest, whatever the tax code says.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="seven-episodes-seven-verdicts" aria-labelledby="seven-episodes-seven-verdicts-heading">
          <h2 id="seven-episodes-seven-verdicts-heading">Seven episodes, seven verdicts</h2>
          <h3 id="1991-1997-stabilization-that-worked">1991-1997: stabilization that worked</h3>
          <p>
            The Convertibility Plan of April 1991 pegged the peso 1:1 to the dollar with (mostly) full reserve backing. It killed hyperinflation dead and, together with privatization, deregulation and trade opening, produced <a href="https://www.imf.org/external/np/ieo/2003/arg/index.htm" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">average growth near 6% through 1997</a>. Calling this period an unqualified neoliberal failure is simply false. The mistake was believing early stabilization had permanently solved the fiscal, debt and institutional problems underneath.
          </p>
          <h3 id="1998-2002-a-doomed-regime-defended-too-long">1998-2002: a doomed regime defended too long</h3>
          <p>
            The peg removed the exchange rate as a shock absorber just as the shocks arrived: a strong dollar, Brazil's 1999 devaluation and the post-1998 emerging-market sudden stop. <a href="https://users.nber.org/~confer/2002/argentina02/velasco2.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Hausmann and Velasco</a> estimated the peso was overvalued by 40% or more by 2001, while dollar-denominated public and private debt meant devaluation would detonate balance sheets. They also showed that primary spending as a share of GDP did not balloon over 1993-2001. The fiscal rot came from provincial deficits, rising interest costs and above all the 1994 pension privatization, whose transition the <a href="https://www.imf.org/-/media/websites/imf/imported-full-text-pdf/external/np/ieo/2004/arg/eng/pdf/_report.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">IMF's Independent Evaluation Office</a> later costed at no less than 2.7% of GDP a year by 2001, introduced with no credible way to pay for it. GDP per capita fell 22% from 1998 to 2002, poverty passed 50% and Argentina defaulted on roughly $100 billion, then the largest default in history. The IEO's verdict on the Fund itself was blunt: it "erred by supporting inadequate policies too long" and committed up to $22 billion from late 2000 to defend a peg its own staff increasingly knew was unsustainable, with no contingency plan for exit.
          </p>
          <h3 id="2003-2011-the-boom-that-bought-nothing-durable">2003-2011: the boom that bought nothing durable</h3>
          <p>
            Recovery was fast (8-9% growth a year through 2007) thanks to idle capacity, a cheap peso and the commodity supercycle. The failure was converting none of it into institutions: no stabilization fund, no structural surplus, no independent central bank, no deep peso capital market. Chile and Norway built savings mechanisms in the same boom; Argentina built energy subsidies, export taxes of up to 35% on soy and, in 2008, the nationalization of roughly $25-30 billion in private pension assets. Statistics falsification began in 2007. When prices turned, the spending commitments stayed and the revenues left.
          </p>
          <h3 id="2011-2015-controls-instead-of-correction">2011-2015: controls instead of correction</h3>
          <p>
            Rather than fix the widening deficit, the government imposed capital controls (the cepo, November 2011), expropriated 51% of YPF from Repsol (2012), ran multiple exchange rates, capped prices and rationed imports through the DJAI licensing system, under which <a href="https://www.nber.org/system/files/working_papers/w32037/w32037.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">about 30% of applications, covering 36.5% of requested import value, were simply denied</a>; an NBER study estimates the restrictions raised importers' input prices by around 4%. Stagnation set in. The 2014 pari passu ruling by Judge Griesa in the NML holdout litigation tipped Argentina into another technical default and prolonged its exile from credit markets.
          </p>
          <h3 id="2015-2019-liberalization-financed-the-riskiest-way-possible">2015-2019: liberalization, financed the riskiest way possible</h3>
          <p>
            Macri lifted the cepo, cut export taxes and floated the peso, but paired those changes with fiscal gradualism and heavy external dollar borrowing. He reopened the capital account before establishing fiscal credibility, low inflation or an export base to service the debt. When global conditions turned in 2018, the sudden stop arrived on schedule and Argentina signed the <a href="https://www.imf.org/-/media/files/publications/cr/2021/english/1argea2021001.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">largest program in IMF history</a>: $50 billion, raised to $57 billion (1,277% of quota). About $44 billion was disbursed. Only 4 of 12 reviews were ever completed.
          </p>
          <h3 id="2019-2023-back-to-the-printing-press">2019-2023: back to the printing press</h3>
          <p>
            The cepo returned in 2019, followed by a ninth default and restructuring in 2020, price controls, export bans and monetary financing that reached roughly 7% of GDP in the pandemic year. Inflation reached 211.4% in 2023, its highest rate since the tail of the 1990 hyperinflation, and ran at 25.5% per month by December.
          </p>
          <h3 id="2023-2026-the-milei-test">2023-2026: the Milei test</h3>
          <p>
            Milei inherited, in the Cato Institute's <a href="https://www.cato.org/blog/one-year-javier-milei" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">summary</a>, inflation above 200%, poverty around 40%, a combined fiscal and quasi-fiscal deficit near 15% of GDP and a bankrupt central bank. He cut real spending about 30%, turned a 4.6%-of-GDP deficit into a <a href="https://www.cato.org/blog/two-years-milei-reform-agenda-moves-forward-argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">0.3% financial surplus in 2024, the first since 2010</a> and ended monetary financing. Monthly inflation fell from 25.5% to about 2%; annual inflation fell from 117.8% in 2024 to 31.5% in 2025. Most currency controls were lifted in April 2025, backed by a new <a href="https://www.imf.org/en/news/articles/2025/04/12/pr25101-argentina-imf-executive-board-approves-48-month-usd20-billion-extended-arrangement" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">$20 billion IMF Extended Fund Facility</a> (479% of quota, $12 billion up front). The economy contracted 1.7% in 2024, then grew by more than 4% in 2025. <a href="https://www.batimes.com.ar/news/argentina/sharp-drop-in-argentinas-poverty-rate-delivers-boost-for-milei.phtml" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Poverty fell from a peak of 52.9% in early 2024 to 28.2% in the second half of 2025</a>, the lowest since 2018. The October 2025 midterms made his party the largest in the lower house; Congress has since passed fiscal, trade and labor legislation. Reserve targets were <a href="https://www.imf.org/-/media/files/publications/cr/2025/english/1argea2025003-source-pdf.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">missed and waived</a> in 2025, the peso is still contested as overvalued and the IMF's <a href="https://www.imf.org/en/news/articles/2026/05/21/pr26165-argentina-imf-completes-2nd-rev-of-extended-arr-under-eff-concludes-2026-aiv-consultation" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">May 2026 review</a> called performance through end-2025 mixed, with delays in rebuilding external buffers. Two years of stabilization and rebound do not establish sustained convergence.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="the-mistakes-ranked" aria-labelledby="the-mistakes-ranked-heading">
          <h2 id="the-mistakes-ranked-heading">The mistakes, ranked</h2>
          <div class="table-wrap">
